'''John Arthur Stokes''' was a prominent figure in the [[civil rights movement]].<ref name="VCU Libraries">{{cite web|title=Interview with John A. Stokes|url=http://dig.library.vcu.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/voices/id/10|website=VCU Libraries|publisher=[[Virginia Commonwealth University]]|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> He grew up in the [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow South]] and attended [[Robert Russa Moton High School]], a [[segregated school]] for African Americans. Recognizing the inequalities he and his classmates faced, Stokes staged a walk out and refused to return to class until the school was rebuilt.  He attended [[Virginia State University]] and became an educator in [[Baltimore, MD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/trailblazers/2011/stokes.htm|title=The Library of Virginia African American Trailblazer 2011 - John Arthur Stokes|website=www.lva.virginia.gov}}</ref>

